04334nam a22006855i 9781442684317DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426843177 a10.3138/97814426843172doi  a(DE-B1597)497048  a(OCoLC)1078916247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBX4930b.W33 2007eb 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a284.3090311 aWaite, Gary K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEradicating the Devil's Minions :bAnabaptists and Witches in Reformation Europe, 1535–1600 /cGary K. Waite. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Maps -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Devil’s Minions? Anabaptists, Magic, and Witches in the Sixteenth Century -- t2. Blackened Tongues and Miraculous Hosts: Anabaptists and Miracles in the Polemical Literature -- t3. Shamans and Soothsayers: The Persecution of Anabaptists and Witches in the Northern Netherlands -- t4. Rebaptism and the Devil: Anabaptists and Witches in the Southern Netherlands -- t5. The Devil’s Sabbat: Nocturnal Anabaptist Meetings, Hailstorms, and Witchcraft in Southern Germany -- t6. Eliminating the Desecrators of Hosts: Anabaptists and Witches in the Austrian Tirol -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a religious sect, the Anabaptists were seen to practice unusual rituals and follow an eccentric set of beliefs. One story, for instance, purports that an Anabaptist prophet, claiming to have visited heaven, persuaded his followers to run naked through the streets of Amsterdam. Eradicating the Devil's Minions investigates these beliefs in the context of Reformation Europe, a time in which persecution, religious intolerance, and witch-hunting were rampant.Focusing primarily on the Habsburg-controlled regions of Europe, Gary K. Waite argues that the persecution of Anabaptists did not go hand in hand with the outbreak of witch-hunts in the mid-sixteenth century. Rather, distrust of Anabaptists predated the first major witch panic of 1562-3, and Waite suggests that the virulent propaganda against Anabaptist heretics helped convince governments of the existence of a diabolical threat. Although Anabaptists rejected religious magic, they were consistently demonized by Catholic and Lutheran polemicists.Eradicating the Devil's Minions is an investigation into the roots of religious intolerance in Reformation Europe, and a unique examination of mass hysteria and social extremism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnabaptistsxControversial literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aAnabaptistsxHistoryy16th century. 0aDissenters, ReligiouszEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aPersecutionzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aReformation. 0aWitchcraftzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268431740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442684317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442684317.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK